## Daily operating system

### Startup rhythm

- meds
- one preselected movement / regulation rep
- focus music or another reliable transition ritual
- a short typing warmup if useful
- then the main study block

Interpretation:

Startup should minimize live choice.

“Do some physical activity” is too vague when startup resistance is high.
Define the default movement ahead of time.

If the standard version feels too heavy, use a low-energy fallback instead of bargaining with the whole routine.
Low-energy completion still counts as a real startup rep.

Current stabilization rule:
For the current stabilization phase, yoga is the default movement / regulation rep because it reliably improves state and lowers friction.

### Block rule

- prefer one large study block instead of many tiny fragmented topic blocks
- follow the current route sequentially
- supported reps before proving reps when building a new area
- insert systems / code-review work where the roadmap calls for it

### Streaming rule

Streaming can stay in the loop, but real solving needs protected attention.
A proving rep should keep a **silent window**.
Chat interaction during the core solve hurts problem quality.

### Shutdown rule

- write a short retro
- capture at least: wins, losses, blocker type, and tomorrow’s first rep
- choose tomorrow’s specific reps during shutdown
- put them into the task list
- schedule or park open loops instead of carrying them all live
- avoid recurring overdue-task shame spirals

Interpretation:

Shutdown is not optional fluff.
It is a core anti-friction mechanism.

A good shutdown externalizes both progress and friction so the losses do not dominate memory by default.

