## Session handoff rule

At the end of every meaningful build chat, produce a **Session Handoff** block.

Its job is to reduce startup friction for the next chat and prevent important local context from being lost between sessions.

A strong handoff should include:

- what this chat accomplished
- which files were updated
- which major change IDs were touched
- a reminder to update the matching source documents
- what is now true
- what still needs to happen
- the exact goal of the next chat
- and a short paste-start block for the next chat

Interpretation rule:

The handoff is not the historical memory layer.
It is the operational baton pass.

The **System Ledger** records major durable change history.
The **Session Handoff** makes the next work session easier to enter.

### Optional Build Lesson

A handoff may include an optional **Build Lesson** section when a real durable lesson surfaced.

Use it only when one of these is true:

- a recurring project mistake became visible
- the team changed how it builds because the old way was flawed
- a lesson surfaced that should carry across quests or projects
- forgetting the lesson would likely cause repeated waste

Do **not** force a Build Lesson into every handoff.

Interpretation rule:

Forced wisdom becomes noise.
Only record a Build Lesson when it is genuinely worth preserving.

